\begin_layout Standard
Agricultural technology adoption is at the heart of a rich body of research
 on food security, poverty reduction, economic development, and structural
 transformation.
 Studies on the economics of technical change in agriculture go back to
 at least 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "10.2307/1905380"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and are reviewed in widely cited articles such as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "10.2307/1153228"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "sunding2001agricultural"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 More recently and with the proliferation of field experiments and randomized
 controlled trials, economic theories that explore alternative drivers of
 technology adoption have received greater empirical attention.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most of these studies (implicitly) assume that some kind of graduation model
 underlies the technical change process, wherein farmers switch from a low-level
 equilibrium to a high-level equilibrium in which technology use is sustained
 once initial conditions—typically, access to information or finance—are
 satisfied or binding constraints removed 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "karlan2014agricultural,https://doi.org/10.1111/agec.12175,ABATE2016235"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Yet most of these studies follow farmers across a limited number of agricultura
l seasons, and are unable to fully appreciate the dynamics of technology
 adoption over time.
 Only a few studies offer a long-term perspective, with several documenting
 significant levels of dis-adoption 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "doi:10.1080/00220388.2013.874556"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, or transient technology use over time 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1574-0862.2006.00169.x,https://doi.org/10.1111/agec.12721"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the core of our theoretical framework described in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Theoretical-framework"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is a model of learning failures where farmers have inflated expectations
 about the returns to a new technology, but fail to uncover the true form
 of the production function through experience, leading to disappointment
 and subsequent dis-adoption.
 Indeed, heterogeneity in farmer characteristics implies that farmers need
 to learn whether using a new technology is optimal for their specific context
 given costs and benefits 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "suri2011selection"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Farmers learn through a combination of own experiences and observing others
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "foster1995learning,10.1257/aer.100.1.35"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 However, learning about a new technology is often difficult for reasons
 related to the technology's complexity and the observability of its quality
 or performance (i.e., its experience good nature) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "LybbertBell2010,10.1093/qje/qjx009,doi:10.1080/00220388.2018.1464143"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, or the social, psychological, and behavioral attributes of the farmer
 and her learning process 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "foster1995learning,10.1093/qje/qju015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One strand of the literature argues that sequential adoption leads to experienti
al learning by farmers.
 In cases where technologies are bundled in packages, it is often observed
 that farmers sequentially adopt components of the package, rather than
 adopting the entire package at once 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g.,"
key "byerlee1986farmers"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "10.2307/1242825"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 argue that this occurs when farmers employ a Bayesian approach to learning
 in which they try to isolate the impact of one component of the package
 at a time.
 However, there are circumstances under which this strategy is not optimal
 because it can prevent farmers from identifying potential synergies between
 technologies, inputs, and practices.
 Indeed, the reason why many interventions are presented as a package is
 because these interaction effects are not trivial.
 For instance, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1477-9552.2012.00337.x"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 find that banana tissue culture, a technology to ensure that banana plantlets
 are free from pests and diseases, leads to a seven percent yield gain in
 Kenya.
 However, they also find that improving access to irrigation can lift yield
 gains above 20 percent.
 If many complementarities like this exist, it seems unlikely that farmers
 are in a position to follow a sequential learning path that allows for
 all possible interactions between the different technologies within a reasonabl
e time frame.
 Furthermore, as mentioned above, farmers may face certain behavioral constraint
s that inhibit their ability to learn about interaction effects if, for
 example, they pay attention to minor or tangential attributes of the package
 and miss the more important attributes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "10.1093/qje/qju015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Our study contributes to this literature by providing additional evidence
 on the limits of Bayesian learning in the context of agricultural technology
 adoption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another strand of the literature addresses the technology learning process
 in terms of how farmers compare realized yields against expected yields
 to inform their subsequent, longer-term adoption decisions.
 The effect of incorrect expectations about future returns on decision-making
 has been studied most in the context of education, but is readily applicable
 to learning in agriculture.
 For example, both 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "nguyen2008information"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "10.1162/qjec.2010.125.2.515"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 find that providing accurate information about the returns to education
 significantly increases investment in schooling (in Madagascar and the
 Dominican Republic respectively).
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "doi:10.1086/703868"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 finds that a video intervention that informs Ugandan farmers about the
 returns on intensification investments in rice growing improved practices
 and increased input use and production.
 Note that across these studies, it is assumed that the individual underestimate
s the returns in question.
 In our study, as a result of under-investment in complementary inputs,
